  "text": "Another gene expression study on aging identified 1,254 genes that are altered in expression during aging. The tissue-specificity of these genes revealed that intestine-and oocyte-enriched genes are age-dependent, whereas neuronal, muscle, and pharyngeal genes are not [CITATION_1] . Promoter-binding motif analysis for the upstream region of age-related genes indicated that GATA transcription factor ELT-3 may regulate transcriptional changes involved in aging. The expression of elt-3 is reduced in a tissue-specific manner with aging, and two repressors of ELT-3, elt-5 and elt-6, are induced in expression during aging. These findings suggest that an elt3/elt-5/elt-6 GATA transcription circuit plays a pivotal role in normal aging of C. elegans [CITATION_2] . Golden and Melov reported the transcriptional profile of individual aging nematodes. They analyzed the gene expression of 4-5 individual worms at four different ages with a cDNA array containing 921 stress-related genes. Among them, 40 genes were significantly changed in expression as a function of time, including several hsp-16 family genes [CITATION_3] .",
